Neonicotinoids Homology Heatmap Tutorial

Alistair Bailey

23 February, 2017

This notebook demonstrates how to obtain neonicotinoid sequences and perform sequence alignment using Bio3d, and then plot the sequence homologies as heatmaps using ggplot2.

Setting up

First load the packages. If they aren’t installed, use the install.packages function.

# Load packages
library(bio3d)
library(reshape2)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(cowplot)

Getting the sequences and doing an alignment.

The following code shows how to start with four neonicotinoid protein IDs, align them using MUSCLE and then use them to do a wider search for more sequences using HMMER.

The HMMER search yields 253 sequences of which the top 40 are subsetted, just to make visulisation easier.

The subset of 40 sequences are aligned and the homology caclulated both in terms of percentage identity and percentage similarity.

# Get neonicotinoids sequences and save file
seqs <- get.seq(c("P32297","P43681","P36544.5","P36544.5","Q6QHT2"),outfile = "four_seqs.fasta")
# Do initial alignment, this assumes MUSCLE is installed on your machine
# alignment is saved as a fasta file
aln <- seqaln(seqs, outfile="aln_four.fa")
# Do HMMER search for homologous sequences in the SWISSPROT database
hm_srch <- hmmer(aln,type='hmmsearch',db="swissprot",timeout = 30)
# Get the HMMER search sequences 
hm_seqs <- get.seq(hm_srch$hit.tbl$acc2)
# Get top 40 hits and save sequences
hm_sub <- get.seq(hm_srch$hit.tbl$acc2[1:40],outfile = "forty_seqs.fasta")
# Do HMMER aln and save alignment
hm_aln <- seqaln(hm_sub,outfile="aln_forty.fa")
# Calculate sequence similarity using HMMER alignment
sim.mat <- seqidentity(hm_aln,similarity = T)
# Calculate sequence identity  using HMMER alignment
ide.mat <- seqidentity(hm_aln,similarity = F)

Tidy up homology data for plotting

# Copy matrices
id.map <- ide.mat 
sim.map <- sim.mat
# Keep only upper half of each homology matrix
id.map[lower.tri(id.map)] <- NA
sim.map[lower.tri(sim.map)] <- NA

# Melt the matrices for plotting using the reshape2 package
# This creates rows with Protein IDs in columns 1 & 2, Var1 and Var2, 
# and the homology for the pair of sequences in column 3
melted_id.map <- melt(id.map, na.rm=TRUE,value.name = "Percent.Identity")
melted_sim.map <- melt(sim.map, na.rm = TRUE,value.name = "Percent.Similarity")

Plot the homology heatmaps using ggplot2

# Identity map

# melted_id.map is the data,
# the aesthetics are Var2 the Protein ID and Var1 the Protein ID, with
# the homology value mapped to the fill colour. Var2 and Var1 could be the 
# other way round. I just did it so the triangle was at the bottom of the plot
id_heatmap <- ggplot(melted_id.map, aes(Var2,Var1,fill=Percent.Identity)) +
  # Use the tile geom for heatmap.   
  geom_tile() +
  # This code creates a blue to red scale for increasing homology and labels it.
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", mid = "white",
                       high = "red", midpoint = 0.5,
                       limit = c(0,1), space = "Lab",
                       guide = "colourbar",
                       name="Percent.Identity") +
  # Use the minimal theme
  theme_minimal() + 
  # Resize the text on the axis and angle it by 45 degrees
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, 
                                   size = 6, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, 
                                   size = 6, hjust = 1)) +
  # Keep aspect ratio fixed
  coord_fixed() + 
  # Add the homology values as text to each tile
  geom_text(aes(Var2, Var1, label = Percent.Identity),
            color = "black", size = 1) +
  # Remove ticks and titles, resize the text, and move the colorbar.
  theme(
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    legend.justification = c(1, 0),
    legend.position = c(0.5, 0.8),
    legend.direction = "horizontal")+
  guides(fill = guide_colorbar(barwidth = 7, barheight = 1,
                               title.position = "top", title.hjust = 0.5))

# Similarity map

# Same as previous plot
sim_heatmap <- ggplot(melted_sim.map, aes(Var2,Var1,fill=Percent.Similarity)) +
  # Use the tile geom for heatmap.   
  geom_tile() +
  # This code creates a blue to red scale for increasing homology and labels it.
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", mid = "white",
                       high = "red", midpoint = 0.5,
                       limit = c(0,1), space = "Lab",
                       guide = "colourbar",
                       name="Percent.Similarity") +
  # Use the minimal theme
  theme_minimal() + 
  # Resize the text on the axis and angle it by 45 degrees
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, 
                                   size = 6, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, 
                                   size = 6, hjust = 1)) +
  # Keep aspect ratio fixed
  coord_fixed() + 
  # Add the homology values as text to each tile
  geom_text(aes(Var2, Var1, label = Percent.Similarity), color = "black", size = 1) +
  # Remove ticks and titles, resize the text, and move the colorbar.
  theme(
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    legend.justification = c(1, 0),
    legend.position = c(0.5, 0.8),
    legend.direction = "horizontal")+
  guides(fill = guide_colorbar(barwidth = 7, barheight = 1,
                               title.position = "top", title.hjust = 0.5))

Viewing the heatmaps

Save the output as pdf file

# This code saves a landscape pdf "A4r" using plot_grid from the 
# cowplot package to add figure labels 
pdf("homology_heatmap_v1.pdf",paper = "A4r",width=11.5)
plot_grid(id_heatmap,sim_heatmap,labels = c("A","B"))
dev.off()
